Four Clues to Finding Broken Systems

Systems are a helpful tool for maintaining an efficient business.

I’ve written previously about the importance of periodically stepping back and taking a look at your business as a whole to find where your systems are broken or not functioning well.

Here are a few keys to find the places where you lack systems:

**Lots of decisions on routine tasks.** There’s no need to make decisions about tasks you do regularly. Set up a system--a habit, precedent, procedure--to follow every time you or your employees execute that task. Every decision you make takes up time and mental energy. Don’t waste it on routine tasks. Save it for the critical strategic decisions.

**Continual mistakes.** Think of your systems as a path through the woods. A path shows you exactly where to go and guarantees you’ll end up at the same spot every time. If you or your employees are consistently making mistakes, it means the path through the forest is misdirected or unclear. Clear a path through that forest and you’ll begin to eliminate routine mistakes.

**Questions repeatedly asked.** “Hey boss, what should we do about our client Fred’s thingamajig?” If it’s the same thingamajig as client Sarah and client Erin, you need a system to clarify the procedure.

**Confusion about who’s in charge.** If you find yourself mediating between lack of leadership or overzealous power struggles, you should clarify who does what and who answers to whom. Do you want Employee Buck as the general decision maker on the floor? Or does Buck just make the decisions for Department A, while Employee Doe makes the decisions for Department B? Whatever you decide, make it clear who does what and who answers to whom.

Instituting systems like these will not only free up time and mental energy, but will also reduce the stress within your business and between your employees.

Systems are your allies, not your enemies. Use them. Let them evolve and change. Constantly update and fix them. But whatever you do, use them and make them your friends, and they *will* be your friends.
